## Running the Project

### Streamlit Dashboard

```bash
streamlit run app.py
```

### Simple Showcase Simulation

Use this version for a clean teacher-facing demonstration of the title and rubric without extra complexity:

```bash
streamlit run showcase_app.py
```

### CLI Demo Run

```bash
python main.py --model logistic_regression --population-size 28 --generations 18 --mutation-rate 0.18
```

On this machine, validation was performed with:

```bash
C:\Users\LENOVO\anaconda3\python.exe -B main.py --model logistic_regression --population-size 28 --generations 18 --mutation-rate 0.18
```

## Streamlit UI Highlights

The dashboard is designed as a mini analytical product rather than a basic script runner.

- Sidebar controls for population size, mutation rate, generations, and model family
- Hero section with a presentation-style overview
- Tabs for Overview, Results, Graphs, Prediction, and Severity GA
- A Severity GA tab that implements multi-output Random Forest prediction for UCI severity class and derived risk level
- Live GA progress updates and spinner feedback during optimization
- Color-coded metric cards for accuracy, time, and fitness
- Interactive Plotly charts for:
  - accuracy vs. generations
  - training time vs. generations
  - composite fitness vs. generations
  - Pareto front visualization
- Clean presentation of the best hyperparameters and top Pareto candidates
- A patient-detail form that uses the selected model to estimate heart disease presence probability
- A second patient-detail form that uses GA-selected features to predict both severity class and risk level

## Example Output

Sample CLI run for the Logistic Regression configuration saved under `outputs/logistic`:

```text
========================================================================
CardioGA Optimization Report
========================================================================
Model Family          : Logistic Regression
Completed Generations : 14
Stopped Early         : True

Default vs Optimized
  Validation Accuracy : 85.25% -> 88.52%
  Validation Time     : 10.63 ms -> 10.45 ms
  Test Accuracy       : 88.52% -> 88.52%
  Test Time           : 12.21 ms -> 11.70 ms
  Composite Fitness   : 0.7927 -> 0.8166
```

## What the Result Means

In the sample run, the GA found a Logistic Regression configuration that:

- Increased validation accuracy from `85.25%` to `88.52%`
- Slightly reduced validation training time from `10.63 ms` to `10.45 ms`
- Preserved held-out test accuracy at `88.52%`
- Slightly reduced held-out test training time from `12.21 ms` to `11.70 ms`

That is a solid multi-objective outcome: the GA found a configuration that improved validation accuracy, preserved final test accuracy, and held training time essentially flat with a slight speed gain.

## Notes for Viva / Presentation

- The GA is not a black box because every step of selection, crossover, mutation, elitism, and Pareto ranking is written explicitly in code.
- The held-out test split is kept separate from the GA search loop, which makes the final comparison more defensible.
- The dashboard explains dominance, Pareto efficiency, and the rationale behind the selected solution directly inside the UI.
- Result files are exported to `outputs/latest_results.json`, `outputs/generation_history.csv`, and `outputs/pareto_front.csv`.
- Because training time is measured live on the local machine, the exact speed-focused Pareto winner can shift slightly if the system is under different background load.
